<DOC><DOCNO> AP880506-0077 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-88 0826EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Denmark-Greenpeace     05-06 0153</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Denmark-Greenpeace,0160</SECOND><HEAD>Greenpeace, Soviet Warship Clash off Denmark</HEAD><DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Anti-nuclear protesters in dinghiestoday confronted a Soviet navy ship and stuck a radiation sign onits hull, Danish radio reported.   A dinghy overturned with two members of the protest groupGreenpeace, but no one was injured.   The confrontation in the Great Belt Strait off Denmark came fourdays before a parliamentary election whose main issue is thecountry's ban on peacetime nuclear weapons. Government leaders havecalled the vote a referendum on continued membership in NATO.   The environmentists put the radiation sign on the hull of a shipbelieved to be of the Krivak class, which has nuclear capability.   Danish Foreign Minister Uffe Ellemann-Jensen criticized theirprotest as a disruption of legitimate international traffic.   ``It was not very polite to our Soviet friends,'' he said.``They are within their full right to pass through internationalwaters with nuclear arms.''</TEXT></DOC>